                        <li>
                            <i class="icon icon-plus"></i>
                            <div>
                                <a id="pricing_redis_how-to-charge">How do we charge the data transferred to and from the cache?</a>
                                <section>
                                    <p>Charge the data transferred to and from the cache at the <a id="redis_question_transfer" href="/pricing/details/data-transfer/" target="_blank">normal rate</a>.</p>
                                </section>

                            </div>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <i class="icon icon-plus"></i>
                            <div>
                                <a id="pricing_redis_what-charge">Can I scale the Azure Redis Cache Unit (similar to the concept of Hosted Cache)?</a>
                                <section>
                                    <p>Yes. You can expand to multiple Redis Cache Units at the Premium level.</p>
                                </section>

                            </div>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <i class="icon icon-plus"></i>
                            <div><a id="pricing_redis_which-cache-should-be-used">Which kind of cache will be used if I want to create a new cache in Azure?</a><section>
                                    <p>It’s recommended that Azure Redis Cache be deployed and used thanks to its flexibility. This cache is based on an open standard Redis agreement supported by many programming languages (C/C++, .NET, Go, Java, Node.js, Objective C, Perl, PHP, Python, and Ruby, as well as over 29 more languages). Thus, almost any workload generated in Azure may use this cache.</p>
                                </section>

                            </div>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <i class="icon icon-plus"></i>
                            <div>
                                <a id="pricing_redis_managed-cache">Since you recommend using Redis, why not provide the recommended “Hosted Cache” option?</a>
                                <section>
                                    <p>This aims to support the customers who make investment on the shared cache they rely on, enabling them to have sufficient time to migrate to Redis Cache.</p>
                                </section>
                            </div>
                        </li>
